		<item>
		<title>Awesome Fingerboard Shifting Exercise (L#152)</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/technique/fingerboard-shifting-exercise-bass-lesson.html</link>
		<comments>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/technique/fingerboard-shifting-exercise-bass-lesson.html#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 03 Mar 2015 13:34:39 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[scott]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Beginners]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Technique]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/?p=10019</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>As bass players we’re constantly playing up and down the fingerboard and changing positions as our bass lines, grooves and solos dictate. One of the most common mistakes I see students make time and time again when making these fingerboard...</p>
<p>The post <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/technique/fingerboard-shifting-exercise-bass-lesson.html">Awesome Fingerboard Shifting Exercise (L#152)</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com">Online Bass Lessons</a>.</p>
]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>As bass players we’re constantly playing up and down the fingerboard and changing positions as our bass lines, grooves and solos dictate. One of the most common mistakes I see students make time and time again when making these <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/technique/speed-shifting-exercises-bass-lesson.html" target="_blank">fingerboard shifts</a> or going for larger jumps on the fingerboard is where their attention is focused<em> at the exact moment of the shift</em>.</p>
<p>Most of the time players are so consumed with what their fretting hand is doing, that when shifting to a new position they’re still focused solely on their <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/technique/2-great-tips-perfect-fretting-hand-technique.html" target="_blank">fretting hand</a> - <em>and not where they’re about to shift to.</em> This is exactly what leads to floppy shifts, landing on the wrong finger, and more often that not even landing on the wrong fret!</p>
<p>In this lesson I’m going to get laser focused on this topic and give you an awesome<a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/improvisation/ear-training-exercise-bass.html" target="_blank"> </a>exercise to break this bad habit for good!</p>
<p>As always, see you in the shed…</p>
<p>Scott :)</p>
</p>
<p>PS. If you really want to nail down your technique and become a "Bass Technique Ninja" ;) ... check out my full technique course in <a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/courses/technique-deep-dive-for-bass">The Academy here</a>. It's FULL of cool exercises like this one.</p>
